International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: 14 Dec 2007
Source: Australian Broadcasting Corporation News [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/12/14/2118888.htm>


More cases of the cane fungal disease smut are expected to be found in
north Queensland by the new year [2008].

A Proserpine grower found an infected stool on his property earlier this
week while applying herbicides from a high clearance tractor. The BSES
[Bureau of Sugar Experimental Stations] confirmed the disease and destroyed
the infected plant. Inspections of nearby properties failed to find any
other instances of smut.

But Peter Sutherland from the BSES says more cases are inevitable. "We'd
expect, by the nature of that infection and the disease, that it'll pop up
between now and February [2008] again, so cane's actively growing at the
moment, and we still have quite a bit of Q157 [smut susceptible variety] in
the area," he said. "So I expect as other operations are carried out from
these high clearance tractors that growers will actually spot it."

