******
[2]
Date: 26 Nov 2007
Source: North Queensland Register [edited]
<http://nqr.farmonline.com.au/news_daily.asp?ag_id=47123>


The inevitable has been confirmed, with the detection of smut in the
Maryborough area showing that the productivity-stunting sugarcane disease
is continuing to spread.

But producer group Canegrowers says the area is already ahead of the game
with a plan of attack well under way. Canegrowers' acting chief executive,
Ron Mullins, says responsible growers have started a program of replacing
susceptible varieties with resistant varieties, a vital step in minimising
the economic impact of the disease. "The Maryborough sugarcane industry had
been bracing itself for this moment for some time, so when suspect smut
whips were found on a property in the area last week, they stepped up work
on the intensive management strategies needed to minimise the impact of
this potentially devastating disease," Mr Mullins said.

Smut is a debilitating fungal disease which, in its worst form, can
dramatically reduce productivity and ultimately kill sugarcane plants.
Spread by infected spores, the disease can be carried on contaminated
machinery and even clothing and skin. But, according to Canegrowers, the
biggest hurdle to combating the windborne disease is breeding and planting
resistant varieties, a process which will take many years.

The disease was 1st discovered on the eastern seaboard in the Bundaberg
Isis region mid last year [2006], followed closely by a 2nd outbreak, which
was identified in the Mackay area. Its discovery in the Ingham area late
last year was further confirmation that the disease was here to stay.

"The response plans drawn up locally have been under way for some 12 months
now," Mr Mullins said. "They seek to manage disease levels and reduce
economic impacts. The only truly effective measure against the impact of
smut is to replace susceptible varieties with those with high levels of
resistance to the fungal strain." The downside is that resistant varieties
are also characterised by reduced productivity, but Mr Mullins is confident
that with time and resources this can be overcome.

[byline: Canegrowers and Queensland Country Life]

