******
[3]
Date: 23 Nov 2007
Source: North Queensland Register [edited]
<http://nqr.farmonline.com.au/news_daily.asp?ag_id=47094>


In response to the increase in sugarcane smut disease in the Herbert River
region, Qld, the Bureau of Sugar Experiment Stations (BSES) Limited will
host a public meeting to discuss varieties of sugarcane resistant to smut.

Senior extension officer of BSES' principal research and development, Greg
Shannon, said the recent dry condition of the soil is one of the factors
contributing to the increase in sugarcane smut. He said at least 17 of the
26 Herbert productivity zones have at least one farm with smut. Mr Shannon
said, "We are identifying 1-2 farms per day showing the classic smut whip
symptoms. Approximately 600 hectares are affected by sugarcane smut in the
Herbert. BSES is undertaking surveillance in the Stone River, Lannercost,
and Macknade areas as well as in sugarcane varieties Q157, Q158, and Q174A."

Mr Shannon said that at the meeting, "Dr Nils Berding, principal research
scientist, will discuss the BSES plant breeding program for smut resistant
cane which began in 1999. Dr Rob Magarey, also a BSES pincipal research
scientist, will outline the new Smut Epidemiology study for the Herbert
which commenced in October [2007]."

[byline: Queensland Country Life]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Sugarcane smut is caused by the fungus _Sporisorium scitamineum_
(previously _Ustilago scitaminea_). It is highly infectious and can be
spread by wind or carried on clothing and machinery. Symptoms are a black
whip-like structure emerging from the central core of meristematic tissues.
It contains spores covered with a thin membrane which ruptures easily to
release the spores.

The best control method is to use resistant cultivars available for
different cane growing regions. Careful removal of infected plants after
covering the whip may help prevent secondary spread of the disease. Smut
spores survive for long periods in soil or plant debris. Thus, the disease
is also managed by burning of infected fields after harvest and the use of
healthy seedcane setts from disease-free nurseries for replanting. Soaking
of setts in a solution of fungicide or short hot-water treatment may also
help to control smut.

Sugarcane smut appears to be present in every sugarcane-growing country
worldwide. Australia was the last country considered to be free of this
disease until smut was found in 1998 in Western Australia, a minor cane
growing area. In June 2006, it was found in Queensland where it has spread
to all the main Australian sugar growing regions within the last 18 months,
despite efforts to contain the disease. The industry had been preparing for
a smut incursion for years, screening varieties for smut resistance, and
this has placed growers in a fairly good position to minimise losses. Smut
management plans have been implemented, for example the movement of
sugarcane and sugarcane machinery is now restricted in Queensland by a
Plant Protection Act. Smut monitoring (by spore traps and susceptible
indicator plots) and development of high-yielding resistant cultivars
continues. A programme of replacing susceptible with smut resistant
varieties is in progress. Replacement is mandatory when replanting, but
ratoon crops of already planted susceptible varieties may still be
harvested. It will, therefore, take several years before a complete
transition to resistant varieties will be achieved.

